Every time I try to forecast on Brexit I get a headache and need to take lots of breaks, get a glass of water, etc. The whole thing is a giant mess and there are several impossible tasks that people are trying to complete by impossible deadlines. As of S&P's last assessment ("maintain") in Oct 2017, they hadn't even started the 2nd phase of negotiations, and this was viewed as a major risk. Fortunately, in mid-Dec 2017, they did start the 2nd phase, which is ongoing. From my cursory reading of the news, they need to settle: (i) usual trade issues, there will be posturing, but ultimately it's in everyone's best interest to reach a deal, so I think they will reach one, even if after a transitional period;
(ii) some freedom of movement issues, e.g. what happens to EU nationals currently living in UK, and vice-versa --- these don't strike me as hard to find agreement on;
(iii) the issue with the Irish border, which is mathematically impossible to solve. However, it is small and localized enough that they may simply pretend like they solved it, without actually solving it, in the interests of getting a deal and stability. UK exit from EU happens in mid-March 2019. The question deadline, ~6 months before that, strikes me as a bit early to have S&P form a judgment on how Brexit will turn out. Especially if there's a transitional period --- which, as far as I can tell, is against nobody's interests, so is quite likely to be implemented. The indicators that S&P said [1] they would look out for in possible future downgrades seem like big things to me, that would take a long time to materialize or detect trends in: changes in GDP per capita, amount of GBP held as reserve currency by central banks around the world, capital inflows/outflows... without these concrete numbers, which I don't think we'll have by Sep 2018, they have to go off of the progression of negotations, which as I argued will probably not look awful by Sep. Based on all this I wanted to say 90% "no adjustment", 10% "down". But crowd is much less certain than that, so I take account of its wisdom and say 80/20. [1] https://www.standardandpoors.com/en_US/web/guest/article/-/view/type/HTML/id/1939008

Adjusting down slightly for the present: "The euro surged against rivals on Friday, hitting a three-year high against the dollar after German lawmakers reached an agreement on a blueprint for a ruling coalition between Chancellor Angela Merkel’s Christian Democrats and the opposing Social Democrats.  "Also in Europe, the British pound moved to its highest level since the U.K.’s vote to leave the European Union on the back of reports suggesting the Netherlands and Spain want to work toward a “soft” Brexit...."
https://www.marketwatch.com/story/euro-hits-3-year-high-on-breakthrough-for-german-coalition-talks-dollar-weak-ahead-of-data-2018-01-12 "Fitch: credit quality [for the UK] now highest since 2008 
Credit rating agency Fitch has added to the optimistic mood in the markets, by reporting that the outlook for credit is the best in a decade. Fitch reports that the number of likely credit upgrades in 2018 and 2019 outnumbers potential downgrades by the most since 2008.  But it also warns that this may be as good as it gets - some companies could find it harder to service their debts once interest rates rise higher. Monica Insoll, a Fitch managing director, explains: “The rating outlook trend is the most upbeat in a decade, with positive outlooks outnumbering negatives. But the net bias is only just over 1% and occurs as the world is about to hit peak growth in the current cycle. The continued tightening of monetary policy, together with significant policy and political uncertainty, is likely to pose increasing challenges to ratings....”
https://www.theguardian.com/business/live/2018/jan/08/stock-markets-rally-shares-asia-eurozone-mothercare-profits-warning-business-live Given 1)  that the agencies tend to be within the same general range (https://countryeconomy.com/ratings), 2) that the current Brexit negotiations seem to be moving along rather well and have come to some general agreement on the debt repayment even if the details haven't been negotiated yet, and also 3) that the general economic outlook seems to be looking rather batter than the depressing slide from last year even if it's still just barely breaking even --> it seems reasonable to expect that the UK won't be downgraded again unless things take an unexpected turn for the worse (remaining Brexit negotiations, other economic issues, serious political crisis, etc).  Generally markets don't react well to downgrades to the world's strongest and most stable markets, and I think S&P won't issue a downgrade until it's a warning more likely to stabilize markets and warn off investors. S&P's warning that they might downgrade last summer was seen at the time as weaker than Moody's who did end up downgrading (http://www.businessinsider.com/sp-and-moodys-uk-credit-rating-general-election-cut-2017-6?r=UK&IR=T; also see @dsarin's useful paste of S&P's comments on their Oct decision not to downgrade http://www.gjopen.com/comments/comments/672696).  One of the concerns cited in the fall by Fitch & S&P for deciding not downgrading when Moody's did was the stability of the Brexit process & May's govt (which hasn't been great but seems to be holding steady as well since December's deal on the first stage of the Brexit negotiations http://www.dw.com/en/british-pm-theresa-may-struggles-on-amid-brexit-uncertainty/a-42026025
http://www.hitc.com/en-gb/2018/01/11/these-latest-brexit-poll-numbers-are-bad-news-for-theresa-may/
https://www.express.co.uk/news/politics/898941/Brexit-Theresa-May-EU-politics-UK-Michel-Barnier-David-Davis-news-latest-European-Union).  Another major issue was the economic strength of the UK and the likelihood that Brexit/EU issues and the generally negative outlook would run off investors and lead them to withdraw existing investments.  Although the situation still looks pretty grim for the UK, it also doesn't seem to look as bad as was generally expected 6 months ago (https://www.ft.com/topics/themes/UK_economic_growth; https://www.theguardian.com/business/2017/dec/31/uk-economy-in-2018-steady-growth-tempered-by-brexit-politics).  S&P's warning last fall (http://www.gjopen.com/comments/comments/672696) touches on a lot of reasonable fears, but the most likely to me seems to be political/constitutional issues re: Scotland & Ireland.  However, Sturgeon is putting off concerns about another Scottish referendum until late summer to see how the second round of Brexit negotiations go (http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/nicola-sturgeon-says-she-wait-for-brexit-deal-to-decide-on-indyref2-a8159046.html).   For now.  Ireland has been much more tenuous, as predicted, over the border issues (https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/monkey-cage/wp/2017/12/04/__trashed/?utm_term=.a0e56d7fc0af; https://www.ft.com/content/983b64e8-d8e0-11e7-a039-c64b1c09b482). Recently Arlene Fosoter, DUP head, has indicated she wants to find some way to work out Brexit decisions and is trying to show willingness for talks but is still taking a hard line on what is needed to keep Ireland's trade and border connections best for Ireland and doesn't seem likely to concede significantly on her core points (https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/jan/13/dup-leader-says-relations-with-irish-republic-not-under-threat-despite-brexit;
https://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/government-welcomes-arlene-foster-s-support-for-closer-links-1.3355323;
http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/brexit-ireland-arlene-foster-uk-mutual-interests-a8157901.html;
https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/dec/08/arlene-foster-brexit-brinkmanship-rooted-in-a-border-childhood;
https://www.express.co.uk/news/uk/904202/Brexit-news-EU-Arlene-Foster-Theresa-May-Britain-Irish-border-Ireland)
Even with some significant concessions, the political situation in Northern Ireland doesn't look good (https://mg.co.za/article/2018-01-09-divided-over-brexit-nireland-marks-year-with-no-government).  The Ireland issue is much too deep into UK politics I don't understand, but it also seems to be the most certain place for political tensions to resist negotiations.  Not that people aren't clearly unhappy with Brexit, the conservative govt and ongoing austerity/economic hardships. The deadline for the second stage of the Brexit negotiations (trade relations & non-trade/security relations isn't until October, so it's not likely to put immediate breaking-point pressure on May, conservatives or the country's financial security.  I'm sure there will continue to be issues that come up, but S&P isn't likely to downgrade immediately - at least a month or more after a major issue, and probably only if it looks like it can't be salvaged, so probably 2-3+ months - which I think decreases odds on a downgrade by Oct even with the remaining uncertainties.  For now it seems like everyone's likely to keep waiting and going about their business.  Maybe things will look more desperate later in the spring & summer.  Certainly the second round of negotiations seems more challenging than anything else so far.
